    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="head" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Veij transeu[n]t ab annuis magistratibus ad Reges: vt Romani &agrave;a Regibus ad annuos Magistratus. Quot capita, tot sententia[e]: tam politica[e], 
                        qu&agrave;m Ethica[e], Oeconomica[e], Technica[e]. Suum cuiq[ue] pulchrum: et humana omnia in circulo circumvolutantur. Roma[e] Reges ante 
                        consules: et Ca[e]sares post Consules: et Pontifices post Ca[e]sares: et post Pontifices, qui potest capere capiat. Quid optimum, Ratio sapientium magistra; 
                        Experientia, stultorum: vtraq[ue] solertium.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The Veians switch from annual magistrates to kings, just like the Romans from kings to annual magistrates. As many people, 
                so many opinions, both political, as ethical, economic, and professional. Each system has its own beauty, and all human affairs revolve. 
                At Rome there were kings before consuls, and emperors after consuls, and bishops after emperors, and after bishops, he who can may take it. 
                The best is when reason leads the wise, experience the foolish; and both of these the clever.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian" anchor_text="&agrave; Gallis Roma capta est">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="left_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Roma, capta &agrave; Gallis.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Rome, captured by the Gauls.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position place="intext" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Furius, &amp; Manlius, two valorous &amp; braue men.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Marcus Furius Camillus"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Manlius Capitolinus"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Furius"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" type="straight" text="Manlius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
